Introduction

Household ID: PC205_PC206

This report provides an overview of the air quality in your home, focusing on PM2.5 concentration levels. PM2.5 concentration levels were determined based on the recorded particle count of fine particulate matter (PM2.5) during the monitoring period. Descriptive statistics and visualizations will be presented to illustrate the findings. According to the World Health Organization (WHO) air quality guidelines 2021, the 24-hour mean PM2.5 concentration should not exceed 15 µg/m3, read more information on WHO air quality guidelines here.

The hourly average ambient (outdoor) PM2.5 concentration levels are incorporated into the visualization of PM2.5 air quality in your home. The historical ambient (outdoor) PM2.5 data is sourced from the National Environmental Agency’s (NEA) API retrieved from data.gov.sg. NEA’s PM2.5 data is split into five regions in Singapore—North, South, East, West, and Central—with readings available every hour. The readings from the region where your home is located are used to represent the outdoor air quality.

Please note that the reported PM2.5 concentrations for your home are uncalibrated values.

The data covers the sampling period from 2025-02-21 to 2025-03-07.

The mean PM2.5 concentration level in your home during the sampling period was below the WHO recommended 24-hour limit of 15 µg/m3, indicating good air quality.
